<!-- Node: "Dan Koppel's interview" -->
<div class="body_box_header">Dan Koppel's interview</div>
<div class="body_box"><small>Submitted by <a href="http://www.gamedesign.net/user/view/2157" title="View user profile.">method</a> on Monday, May 17, 2004 - 18:40</small><br /><br />
<!-- (c)2004 Kingpin_Xatrix -->

I asked <b>Dan Koppel</b> from <a href = "http://www.gmistudios.com/">Gray Matter</a> Studios (Kingpin, RtCW) a few questions about <b>Kingpin</b>, level designing and importance of sketching the level.<br>

<h3>DAN KOPPEL'S INTERVIEW</h3>

<b>RUST:</b> Please tell us about yourself and how you got into gaming business?<br><br>

<b>Dan Koppel:</b> I love playing games and making games. Currently I'm the Design Lead at  Gray Matter Studios. My first game I worked on was Quake 2: The Reckoning. I also worked on Kingpin and Return to Castle Wolfenstein. Before all that I released a few of Quake 1 maps into the community, back then user made SP levels were much more common.
<br /><br />
<a href="http://www.gamedesign.net/comment/reply/260" title="Add a new comment to this page.">Add new comment</a> &middot; <a href="http://assets.aq2world.com/archive/websites/www.gamedesign.net/node/view/260" title="Read the rest of this posting." class="read-more"><b>Read more</b></a> &middot; 105 reads
</div><br />


